diff --git a/CONTRIBUTING.md b/CONTRIBUTING.md
index 6fd8f8f136eb3c76778263c70d48819d5955a85a..0ff33e11c8328a6b5ee113943c9e7e3193596878 100644
--- a/CONTRIBUTING.md
+++ b/CONTRIBUTING.md
@@ -184,6 +184,9 @@ $ run0 rm /var/lib/extensions/zz-gnome-control-center.raw
 $ run0 systemd-sysext refresh
 ```
 
+<details>
+<summary>Expand remote deployment instructions</summary>
+
 On a remote workstation or VM, deploy the system extension by running the following:
 
 ```shell
@@ -205,6 +208,8 @@ $ ssh user@remote-workstation-hostname-or-ip run0 rm /var/lib/extensions/zz-gnome-control-center.raw
 $ ssh user@remote-workstation-hostname-or-ip run0 systemd-sysext refresh
 ```
 
+</details>
+
 ### 7.2 Option 2: By building, serving and updating from a local sysupdate repository (`systemd-sysupdate`)
 
 > This option works best if you want to permanently deploy your changes to your local workstation, a VM, or a different workstation. A reboot is required to see your changes in action. Unlike with the [`systemd-sysext` option](#71-option-1-by-building-and-installing-a-system-extension-systemd-sysext), this option can be used to iterate on the kernel.
@@ -222,6 +227,9 @@ $ run0 utils/enable-local-repo.sh --local # You can skip this step if you're deploying to a VM started with `./utils/run-secure-vm.sh --local-updates`
 $ updatectl update host@l.1 # Without passing `--same-version` to run-sysupdate-repo.sh, the number after `l.` increments on each run
 $ systemctl reboot
 ```
+
+<details>
+<summary>Expand remote deployment instructions</summary>
 
 On a remote workstation or a VM not started with `./utils/run-secure-vm.sh --local-updates`, run the following:
 
@@ -234,17 +242,24 @@ ```
 
 After rebooting, select the new version (`l.1`) from the `systemd-boot` menu. If you're using disk encryption, at the TPM PIN prompt enter your disk recovery key, not your TPM PIN.
 
+</details>
+
 To configure `systemd-sysupdate` on your workstation to no longer use your local repository, run the following:
 
 ```shell
 $ run0 utils/enable-local-repo.sh --clean
 ```
 
+<details>
+<summary>Expand remote cleanup instructions</summary>
+
 On a remote workstation or a VM not started with `./utils/run-secure-vm.sh --local-updates`, run the following:
 
 ```shell
 $ ssh user@remote-workstation-hostname-or-ip run0 /tmp/gnome-build-meta/utils/enable-local-repo.sh --clean
 ```
+
+</details>
 
